{
  "The hardest mineral on the Mohs scale is:": "",
  "Diamond": "",
  "Topaz": "",
  "Corundum": "",
  "Quartz": "",
  "Diamond ranks 10 on the Mohs hardness scale, making it the hardest known natural mineral. It can scratch every other mineral but cannot be scratched by any of them.": "",
  "The softest mineral on the Mohs scale is:": "",
  "Talc": "",
  "Calcite": "",
  "Feldspar": "",
  "Gypsum": "",
  "Talc ranks 1 on the Mohs hardness scale, making it the softest mineral. It can be scratched with a fingernail and has a characteristic greasy or soapy feel.": "",
  "A mineral must have all of the following characteristics EXCEPT:": "",
  "Formed from living organisms": "",
  "Crystalline structure": "",
  "Definite chemical composition": "",
  "Naturally occurring": "",
  "By definition, minerals must be inorganic (not formed from living organisms), naturally occurring, solid, have a definite chemical composition, and possess an orderly crystalline structure.": "",
  "The streak test determines a mineral's:": "",
  "Density": "",
  "Crystal shape": "",
  "Color in powdered form": "",
  "Hardness": "",
  "The streak test involves rubbing a mineral across an unglazed porcelain plate to observe the color of the powdered mineral left behind. Streak color is often more reliable than the mineral's surface color for identification.": "",
  "A mineral that reflects light like polished metal has a _____ luster.": "",
  "Pearly": "",
  "Metallic": "",
  "Earthy": "",
  "Vitreous": "",
  "Metallic luster describes minerals that reflect light strongly like polished metal, such as pyrite and galena. Non-metallic lusters include vitreous (glassy), pearly, earthy, and silky.": "",
  "When a mineral breaks along smooth, flat surfaces, this property is called:": "",
  "Streak": "",
  "Luster": "",
  "Fracture": "",
  "Cleavage": "",
  "Cleavage is the tendency of a mineral to break along flat, smooth planes of weakness in its crystal structure. The number and angles of cleavage planes are important diagnostic features for mineral identification.": "",
  "Specific gravity compares a mineral's density to the density of:": "",
  "Air": "",
  "Iron": "",
  "Water": "",
  "Specific gravity is the ratio of a mineral's density to the density of water (1 g/cm cubed). A mineral with a specific gravity of 5.0, for example, is five times denser than an equal volume of water.": "",
  "Which mineral identification property is considered LEAST reliable?": "",
  "Color": "",
  "Crystal form": "",
  "Color is the least reliable identification property because many minerals come in multiple colors due to impurities. For example, quartz can be clear, white, pink, purple, or smoky, while streak and hardness remain consistent.": "",
  "Calcite can be identified by its reaction with dilute hydrochloric acid, which causes it to:": "",
  "Turn blue": "",
  "Fizz and produce carbon dioxide bubbles": "",
  "Dissolve completely without any reaction": "",
  "Become magnetic": "",
  "Calcite (calcium carbonate, CaCO3) reacts with dilute hydrochloric acid by effervescing and producing carbon dioxide gas. This acid test is one of the most distinctive and quick ways to identify calcite in the field.": "",
  "Silicate minerals dominate Earth's crust because:": "",
  "Silicon and oxygen are the two most abundant elements in the crust": "",
  "They form only in volcanic environments": "",
  "They are the hardest minerals": "",
  "They are the easiest to identify": "",
  "Silicon and oxygen together make up about 75% of Earth's crust by mass. Because these elements are so abundant, silicate minerals (built on silicon-oxygen tetrahedra) make up over 90% of crustal minerals.": "",
  "What is the Mohs hardness scale?": "",
  "A relative scale ranking ten reference minerals from 1 (talc) to 10 (diamond) based on scratch resistance": "",
  "A scale that measures the weight of minerals from lightest to heaviest": "",
  "A numerical measure of how quickly minerals dissolve in acid": "",
  "A scale that classifies minerals by their chemical composition": "",
  "The Mohs hardness scale is a qualitative ordinal scale that ranks ten reference minerals by their resistance to scratching. It ranges from talc (1) to diamond (10), and any unknown mineral can be ranked by testing which reference minerals it can scratch.": "",
  "What is mineral luster?": "",
  "The chemical formula that defines a mineral's composition": "",
  "The color of a mineral when it is ground into powder": "",
  "The tendency of a mineral to break along smooth planes": "",
  "The way a mineral's surface reflects light, described as metallic or non-metallic": "",
  "Luster describes how light interacts with the surface of a mineral. The two main categories are metallic (shiny like metal) and non-metallic, which includes subcategories such as vitreous (glassy), pearly, silky, and earthy.": "",
  "What is cleavage in mineralogy?": "",
  "The resistance of a mineral to being scratched": "",
  "The pattern of colors seen when a mineral is heated": "",
  "The way light passes through a transparent mineral": "",
  "The tendency of a mineral to break along flat, predictable planes determined by its crystal structure": "",
  "Cleavage is the tendency of a mineral to break along smooth, flat planes that correspond to zones of weakness in the crystal structure. Minerals can have one, two, three, or more cleavage directions at specific angles to each other.": "",
  "What is fracture in mineralogy?": "",
  "The irregular or uneven way a mineral breaks when it does not have cleavage planes": "",
  "The smooth, flat surfaces along which a mineral breaks": "",
  "The splitting of a mineral into thin sheets": "",
  "A crack in a mineral caused by weathering": "",
  "Fracture describes how a mineral breaks when it does not break along cleavage planes. Types of fracture include conchoidal (curved, shell-like surfaces as in quartz), fibrous, hackly (jagged), and uneven.": "",
  "What is specific gravity?": "",
  "The gravitational force exerted on a mineral at Earth's surface": "",
  "The volume of water displaced when a mineral is submerged": "",
  "The weight of a mineral measured on a standard laboratory scale": "",
  "A dimensionless ratio comparing a mineral's density to the density of water": "",
  "Specific gravity is the ratio of a substance's density to the density of water. It is dimensionless and helps identify minerals, as each mineral has a characteristic specific gravity. For example, gold has a very high specific gravity of about 19.3.": "",
  "What is a crystalline structure?": "",
  "A random arrangement of atoms with no repeating pattern": "",
  "The external shape of a mineral specimen as found in nature": "",
  "An orderly, repeating three-dimensional arrangement of atoms or molecules within a solid": "",
  "A mineral that is transparent and allows light to pass through": "",
  "A crystalline structure is the orderly, repeating arrangement of atoms, ions, or molecules in three dimensions that defines a mineral. This internal structure determines many physical properties like cleavage, crystal shape, and hardness.": "",
  "What does 'vitreous luster' mean?": "",
  "A luster that looks like polished metal": "",
  "A rainbow-like play of colors on a mineral's surface": "",
  "A dull, rough surface that does not reflect much light": "",
  "A glassy appearance similar to the way light reflects off broken glass": "",
  "Vitreous luster means a glassy appearance, like light reflecting off broken glass. It is the most common type of non-metallic luster and is seen in minerals like quartz, feldspar, and calcite.": "",
  "What is streak in mineral identification?": "",
  "The color of a mineral's powder when rubbed across an unglazed porcelain plate": "",
  "A thin line of impurities visible inside a transparent mineral": "",
  "The direction in which a mineral crystal grows": "",
  "The visible color of a mineral specimen in natural light": "",
  "Streak is the color of the powder left behind when a mineral is scraped across an unglazed porcelain streak plate. It is more reliable than surface color for identification because streak remains consistent even when the mineral's external color varies.": "",
  "What is a silicate mineral?": "",
  "A mineral composed primarily of calcium and carbon": "",
  "A mineral that contains metallic elements like iron and copper": "",
  "A mineral whose crystal structure is based on silicon-oxygen tetrahedra": "",
  "A mineral that forms only in volcanic environments": "",
  "Silicate minerals are built around the silicon-oxygen tetrahedron (SiO4), which is the most common structural unit in Earth's crust. Silicates make up over 90% of the minerals in Earth's crust, including quartz, feldspar, and mica.": "",
  "What is the definition of a mineral?": "",
  "A rock made up of multiple chemical elements": "",
  "Any solid substance found underground": "",
  "Any shiny substance that can be used in jewelry": "",
  "A naturally occurring, inorganic solid with a definite chemical composition and an orderly crystalline structure": "",
  "A mineral is defined by five criteria: it must be naturally occurring, inorganic, a solid, have a definite (or narrowly variable) chemical composition, and possess an orderly internal crystalline structure.": "",
  "A geologist finds a shiny, gold-colored mineral in a stream bed and wants to determine if it is real gold or pyrite (fool's gold). She scratches the specimen across a porcelain plate and observes a greenish-black powder. What does this result tell her?": "",
  "The mineral is neither gold nor pyrite since both leave white streaks": "",
  "The mineral is real gold because gold always leaves a dark streak": "",
  "The mineral is pyrite because real gold leaves a golden-yellow streak, not greenish-black": "",
  "The streak test is inconclusive and she needs to perform an acid test": "",
  "The streak test is an excellent way to distinguish gold from pyrite. Real gold leaves a golden-yellow streak, while pyrite leaves a greenish-black to brownish-black streak. Since this specimen left a greenish-black streak, it is pyrite.": "",
  "A student receives an unknown mineral sample in lab and finds that it can be scratched by a steel nail (hardness 5.5) but not by a copper penny (hardness 3.5). Based on the Mohs scale, which mineral could this sample be?": "",
  "Topaz (hardness 8)": "",
  "Fluorite (hardness 4)": "",
  "Talc (hardness 1)": "",
  "Quartz (hardness 7)": "",
  "Since the mineral is scratched by a steel nail (5.5) but not by a copper penny (3.5), its hardness is between 3.5 and 5.5. Fluorite with a hardness of 4 fits perfectly within this range, while the other options fall outside it.": "",
  "A jeweler is examining two gemstones that look identical in color and shape. She notices that one is significantly heavier than the other for the same size. How could specific gravity help identify the two stones?": "",
  "Specific gravity would not help because it only applies to metallic minerals": "",
  "Each mineral has a characteristic specific gravity, so comparing the measured values to known standards can distinguish between look-alike minerals": "",
  "Specific gravity only measures hardness and would not help with this problem": "",
  "The heavier stone must be fake because real gemstones are always lightweight": "",
  "Specific gravity is a unique physical property for each mineral and can distinguish between minerals that appear similar. By measuring each stone's specific gravity and comparing it to known values, the jeweler can identify what each stone actually is.": "",
  "During a field expedition, a geologist discovers a substance that appears crystalline and has a definite chemical composition, but lab analysis reveals it was produced by a factory and deposited as industrial waste. Is this substance a mineral?": "",
  "Yes, because any solid found outdoors is classified as a mineral": "",
  "No, because industrial waste is always amorphous and cannot form crystals": "",
  "No, because minerals must be naturally occurring, and this substance was produced by human industrial processes": "",
  "Yes, because it has a crystalline structure and definite composition": "",
  "One of the five essential criteria for a mineral is that it must be naturally occurring. Even though this substance has a crystalline structure and definite chemical composition, its origin as industrial waste disqualifies it from being classified as a true mineral.": "",
  "A construction company needs to select a mineral for use as an abrasive in sandpaper. They require a mineral that is hard enough to scratch glass (hardness 5.5) but cheaper than diamond. Which Mohs scale mineral would be a practical choice?": "",
  "Gypsum (hardness 2)": "",
  "Calcite (hardness 3)": "",
  "Corundum (hardness 9)": "",
  "Corundum (hardness 9) is much harder than glass and is commonly used as an industrial abrasive. It is abundant and affordable compared to diamond, making it practical for sandpaper and grinding wheels.": "",
  "A museum curator notices that two specimens of hematite look very different: one is silver-gray and metallic, and the other is reddish-brown and earthy. When both are streak-tested, they leave the same reddish-brown streak. What does this demonstrate?": "",
  "Streak is more reliable than color for mineral identification because it remains consistent regardless of a mineral's external appearance": "",
  "The streak test must be wrong because the minerals clearly have different properties": "",
  "The two specimens must be different minerals since they look so different": "",
  "Color is more reliable than streak and should be used as the primary identification method": "",
  "This scenario illustrates why streak is more reliable than color. Hematite can appear in many different external colors and lusters due to crystal habit and surface conditions, but its streak is consistently reddish-brown, making it a more dependable identification tool.": "",
  "A farmer notices white, crusty deposits forming on the soil surface during dry weather. Lab analysis shows the deposit is gypsum (CaSO4 with 2H2O). If gypsum has a hardness of 2, a vitreous to silky luster, and breaks along flat planes, which identification tests were likely used?": "",
  "Only specific gravity, since that is the only definitive test for gypsum": "",
  "Hardness test (scratched by fingernail), luster observation, and cleavage examination": "",
  "Only the acid test, since gypsum always fizzes in acid": "",
  "Only the streak test, since gypsum has a unique bright orange streak": "",
  "Gypsum (hardness 2) can be scratched by a fingernail (hardness 2.5), making the hardness test straightforward. Combined with its characteristic luster and clear cleavage planes, these three tests together provide reliable identification.": "",
  "A prospector panning for gold in a river collects several heavy, metallic-looking grains. She measures a specific gravity of 5.0 for the sample. If real gold has a specific gravity of about 19.3, what should she conclude?": "",
  "Specific gravity varies too much to be useful and she needs a different test": "",
  "The grains are not gold, since their specific gravity is far too low; they may be pyrite or another dense but non-gold mineral": "",
  "The grains are definitely gold because they are heavy and metallic": "",
  "The grains are gold mixed with a lighter mineral, bringing the average down": "",
  "With a specific gravity of only 5.0 compared to gold's 19.3, these grains are clearly not gold. Pyrite (fool's gold) has a specific gravity of about 5.0, which matches perfectly. This demonstrates why specific gravity is a powerful tool for distinguishing look-alike minerals.": "",
  "An archaeology team finds a stone tool made of obsidian, which is a volcanic glass. A team member argues that obsidian should be classified as a mineral. Why is this classification incorrect?": "",
  "Obsidian is too soft to be classified as a mineral": "",
  "Obsidian is organic because it was shaped by humans": "",
  "Obsidian lacks an orderly crystalline structure because it cooled too rapidly for crystals to form, making it a mineraloid": "",
  "Obsidian does not occur naturally and is always manufactured": "",
  "Obsidian is a volcanic glass that cooled so rapidly from lava that atoms did not have time to arrange into an orderly crystalline structure. Since one of the five defining criteria of a mineral is a crystalline structure, obsidian is classified as a mineraloid, not a true mineral.": "",
  "A geology student is given two white minerals that look nearly identical. Mineral A fizzes when exposed to dilute hydrochloric acid, while Mineral B does not react. Mineral A has a hardness of 3 and Mineral B has a hardness of 4. What are the most likely identities?": "",
  "Mineral A is calcite and Mineral B is fluorite": "",
  "Mineral A is halite and Mineral B is feldspar": "",
  "Mineral A is gypsum and Mineral B is talc": "",
  "Both are quartz since they are both white": "",
  "Calcite (hardness 3) famously fizzes in dilute HCl because it is calcium carbonate. Fluorite (hardness 4) does not react with acid. These two tests together, acid reaction and hardness, clearly distinguish the two minerals despite their similar appearance.": ""
}